deck: Timothy B. Vigil has concentrated mostly in the horror/adult genre of comic books and graphic novels.
description: His initial popular exposure came from his contributions on the comic title Grips while working by the defunct publisher Silverwolf Comics 1986-19867.  Additionally he is a key member of Rebel Studios.  His main character Faust was developed into a movie in 2001 named 2001 movie “Faust: Love of the Damned”. His follow-up story “Faust: Book of M”, was nominated for the 1999 Bram Stoker Award for Best Illustrated Narrative.
name: Tim Vigil

deck: Jonathan Lau is an artist who illustrates almost exclusively for Dynamite titles.
description: The strengths of Lau's work lie in not only realistically drawn figures, but attention to drawing scenery and set objects. His more recent and popular works include collaborations with Kevin Smith on the Bionic Man and The Green Hornet. The Green Hornet lost Kevin Smith as a writer after ten issues but Lau stayed on the creative team for another six, contributing the same explosive pencil work.
name: Jonathan Ang Lau

description:
Career

Carlos Rafael got involved in the comics industry in 2006 when he inked an issue of Red Eagle's adaptation of Robert Jordan's Wheel of Time prequel novel New Spring. Starting that same year and continuing into 2007 he worked for Dynamite Entertainment on several of their Battlestar Galactica issues, working alternately as inker and penciller. In 2007 he also did work on their Highlander comics. He continued to work for Dynamite on a variety of titles and in a variety of capacities from 2008 and continuing on to 2012, doing work for titles including Warlord of Mars, Buck Rogers and Green Hornet, among others.  

Personal Life

Rafael currently lives in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. He began doing art at the age of eighteen, and attended the Graphic Design University in Rio. He has worked for Impacto Studios.
name: Carlos Rafael
